This is a useful command to find the top 10 memory hungry processes on a VPS or dedicated server:

while read command percent rss; do if [[ "${command}" != "COMMAND" ]]; then rss="$(bc &lt;&lt;&lt; &quot;scale=2;${rss}/1024&quot;)&quot;; fi; printf &quot;%-26s%-8s%s\n&quot; &quot;${command}&quot; &quot;${percent}&quot; &quot;${rss}&quot;; done &lt; &lt;(ps -A --sort -rss -o comm,pmem,rss | head -n 11)

It will help to speed up the process of troubleshooting Linux memory usage issues.

For those who search something more C/C++ friendly and that covers float numbers, I suggest something like:

#!/bin/bash

n=20.5;
if [ $( echo "$n &gt; 10" | bc ) -eq 1 ]; then
        echo "Bigger than ten.";
else
        echo "Less or equals ten.";
fi;

